<<image-left "manu prakash.jpg">>Manu Prakash is an Indian born scientist who is a Professor of Bioengineering at Stanford University. Manu was born in Meerut, India and earned a BTech in computer science and engineering from the Indian Institute of Technology in Kanpur. He is best known for his [[Foldscope|https://www.newyorker.com/magazine/2015/12/21/through-the-looking-glass-annals-of-science-carolyn-kormann]] and [[Paperfuge|https://www.wired.com/2017/01/paperfuge-20-cent-device-transform-health-care/]]. [[Prakash received the MacArthur Fellowship|https://www.macfound.org/fellows/965/]] in September 2016. He and his team are also working on a water droplet based computer in Stanford University. His work focuses on frugal innovation that makes medicine, computing and microscopy accessible to more people across the world. 

